,"value":"","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"paragraph"},{"data":{},"content":[],"nodeType":"hr"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":"What Does a Concussion Feel Like?","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"heading-2"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":"The brain generally regains its chemical balance pretty quickly. But in the meantime, you can get some alarming symptoms, including memory loss and brain fog. That’s just what it feels like — your brain is a bit jumbled up and is not making connections as quickly as it usually does.","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"paragraph"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":"A small number of people (typically fewer than","nodeType":"text"},{"data":{"uri":"https://newsinhealth.nih.gov/2013/05/bang-brain"},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":" 10 percent","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"hyperlink"},{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":") still have cognitive issues for weeks or months after the initial injury. However, often this is not ","nodeType":"text"},{"data":{},"marks":[{"type":"italic"}],"value":"directly","nodeType":"text"},{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":" due to the brain injury, explains Hollis. Headache, nausea, and other symptoms of concussion can interfere with sleep, causing cognitive issues. Mood changes or anxiety often follow an accident, and those, too, can mess with your thinking.","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"paragraph"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":"The reason for the injury could also exacerbate the cognitive issues. If the brain injury was due to something traumatic, such as a car accident or even a physical attack, that could lead to post-traumatic stress, which can cause or aggravate cognitive problems.","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"paragraph"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":"“Often what we see in people with post-concussion syndrome is they're dealing with all these other symptoms that are affecting their cognitio